{"key":"processedPost-10427948","value":{"id":10427948,"first":10427144,"last":10427999,"when":1243751364,"utime":"05/31/09 09:29 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />Lastly, the whole point of having the INTAKE on the OUTSIDE of the chamber, and the INPUT on the INSIDE of the chamber, is to create a FLOW of AIR using the natural air movement from the humidifier.</blockquote><br />I'm sure by INPUT, you actually meant 'output'.&nbsp; <br />I've often recommended this method for those who feel they need the extra fresh air.&nbsp; Personally, I just cut slits for FAE.&nbsp; One thing to watch for though:&nbsp; Make sure you have a straight up to the ceiling of the greenhouse shot above the output of the cool mist.&nbsp; They need an unobstructed area or any shelves the mist hits will cause the water to condense and drip back down, making a mess.&nbsp; Make sure the mist doesn't settle into your trays.&nbsp; Waterlogged substrates perform poorly.<br />RR","title":"Re: The K.I.S.S. Martha / Greenhouse. Critiques welcome."}}